    <id>https://www.nber.org/papers/w34574</id>
    <title>Social Security Reforms and Inequality in Japan</title>
    <updated>2025-12-01T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>Takashi Oshio, Satoshi Shimizutani &amp; Akiko S. Oishi</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt; NBER Working Papers&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;We examined the heterogeneous impacts of social security reforms in Japan over the past 40 years. We utilize a nationwide large-scale micro-dataset to compute individual-level social security wealth (SSW) and mortality rates by lifetime earning groups. We found that SSW declined for all groups after the social security reforms, which aimed to reduce generosity; however, the size of the negative impact was larger for richer individuals. These results indicate that a series of recent social security reforms have reduced inequality in SSW.</content>
